14






1350 Grant RdSte 3Mountain View, CA 94040









Fantastic Crew, terrible back office support and terrible infrastructure. Most of the HSBC employees phone agents and tellers have a polite demeanour & best intentions. On the contrary the banking system and norms they use are really painstaking. My time to open an account for a promotion I received was 1 hour and 30 mins, that included a waiting for ~15 mins, account details gathering for ~20 mins, waiting for ~30 mins and then finally ~25 mins with the teller. HSBC corporate run promotions without staffing the local branch with the right infrastructure. In my case, they couldn't accept the check because they let me walk in at 2:30p and by the time they could operate my account they were over 4:00p.

Now let's get to the promotion itself, no one from the call center or the administration team could tell you whether you are on track or not to receive your bonus, in fact the call center team has no clue what promotion you signed up on. They will ask you to reach via Bankmail(their secure messaging platform) and the mail team will redirect you to the call center. Its cyclic! 

Now if you were reading between the lines, my frustration is not the promotion. For a global bank of this footprint, their card systems, online account management, 4 websites before you can sign in, 40 mins of call wait time and the whole experience is so terrible. So in short, not only avoid this branch, (great staff) AVOID THE BANK like plague for domestic US banking at the least.







So my reason visiting the bank was to open a new checking account and take advantage of their promotional sign up. 

First off when entering the bank I was confused and felt lost. The entrance to the bank is not the traditional Chase or BofA. You walk pass the advisers offices before reaching the teller at the end of the hallway. Layout of the bank I would give 1 star because it didn't feel welcoming at all. 

I met the teller first, Christine a traditional Chinese lady. If you understand the Chinese culture then you know what I mean. She handed me some documents to fill out but didn't give me a pen. Luckily I had my own. Towards the end of my trip, she opened up more and I was able to understand the banking process more there. I give her 3.5 stars.

The person who assisted me in opening up my account was Jeff Liao. I was pretty honest with my feelings with the bank and told him I felt foreign in entering the banking facility. He is a very nice person and took the time to explain to me the different options they have. He was pretty patient and was able to answer all the questions I have and even walked me through th online sign on process. I would give him 5 stars, strongly recommend him if you need services at the bank. 

There was another lady, her office was second to the right of the teller. She looked like the Dragon lady at the office. Not friendly or helpful when she saw me and pretty much ignored me. I would give her 0 stars...

I'm just so very glad Jeff made my experience at HSBC bank so much better. Also, I wouldn't recommend coming here in a rush, their computer system is pretty slow.







Great office location which prompted me to open an account here but really bad day to day working 
The asked for all sorts of stupid and unrequited documents - even after DL and 3 credit cards, work ID they asked for home PG&E billing or comcast 
after the account was opened - i kept being logged out and had to re-set my password everytime in some complicated format
When calling you would have to give all details including anything personal - it was PAINFULL and so finally closed the account 

Really bad experience - had to spend 30 min on call to cancel a credit which had not been used for 3 months - if you done tell USA at the end of address - they will question which country so i added planet earth too the address 

Will stick to chase , WF & even BOA







Stay away!

The most atrocious bank of the world and most atrocious branch of the year award goes to HSBC Mountain View. 

1.They will extract as much fee as possible.
2. Even-though you have a premier account, the relationship manager will never contact you. Premier customers are supposed to not wait in the queue with the customer support, but you will end up in a queue.
3.They will recommend you  Mutual funds with higher load. Fiduciary duty for a toss. 
4.They are not open on Weekends and close early at 4pm. 
5.It is hard to understand the Tellers. 

Wells Fargo bank and others are a blessing in comparison.







Jemma B. said it all, really.  Our HSBC experience mirrored hers almost to the letter.  We experienced employees who simply did not know how to handle our seemingly standard requests, but were friendly and, at times, apologetic.  We were 'tag-teamed' on both visits by two women, one who seemed to be some sort of expeditor and one a teller.  This type of interaction meant having to repeat one's request at least twice.  I don't know how this type of scenario is meant to be efficient, which I think might have been the goal, but it wasn't.

The poor slob in line in front of us was in for an address change.  His request, like those of many an HSBC customer in the Bay Area, was one relating to a move from abroad.  We showed up in line behind him fifteen minutes prior to his having had the task completed.  Goodness knows how long he'd already been standing there.  

In my experience, both NYC and UK HSBC banks run a lot more smoothly.  -not sure why the CA affiliate would function any differently, but it does.  Those relocating to the Bay Area with an already existing HSBC acct. would do well to close it and bank elsewhere.







They don't deserved to be called as bank. Reception try to push you out the door by showing her know it all knowledge. Even you point out her mistake, she still refuse to let you to a banker. She just tell you stay where you are and she will going inside and ask. WTF... Canceling my hsbc account right now.







Terrible.

I had an HSBC account in the UK so thought the experience here would be the same. How very wrong I was.

When you walk in it's like a ghost town and when you do finally find someone to help you they pass you from one clueless employee to the next. 

Nothing is simple there - even something as quick as depositing a cheque can take up to half an hour. Couple that with the fact that I have to repeat everything three or four times because the lady who is serving me somehow can't understand my clear London accent?!

If you really feel like you absolutely MUST bank here, ask for Alvin. He seems to be the only person who has any idea what's going on.







Coming to this bank is always an exercise in frustration. I am now using my visits to train myself in principles of mindfulness, detachment, and deep breathing. 

There is always something here to practice deep breathing about, from making me sign again because my signature "doesn't look the same" to performing basic tasks at the speed of molasses. The layout of the branch is absurd. The rest of HSBC's services are similarly terrible, including the non-functioning relationship manager and the app and site which are so secure that I can never log on.







Only if I can give them zero star instead of one. They are simply terrible. They're absolutely the worst bank you can ever meet. The front desk lady is mean, impolite, anti-gay and racist. They ask you questions like they're an immigration officer, And, they are new to gay thing obviously. When I told them I want to open a joint account as a gay couple, the front desk lady simply gave me the ohmygod face which I can never forget. Beside, she doesn't know nothing,nun professional at all.







Odd lay-out, odd employees. Closest location to me *sigh*. Thankfully HSBC is simply an emergency cash account for me and not a main bank holding.

So, when you first walk in you're in a waiting room of sorts with no employee there behind the podium. OK, should I sign in or just sit down? Wait, there is no sign in sheet should I walk down this flat hallway across these glass offices? Ummm...hello? Anyone here?

Finally an account specialist comes out and oh, you just need a teller? It's all the way down at the end of the hallway. Silly me, why didn't I see a teller window ALL THE WAY IN THE BACK? How could I not see the invisible signs that read "This way, idiot?".

Ah, the teller window...why hello cranky teller who looks at me like I just woke him up or interrupted his favorite cat youtube video. Zero professionalism and actually the person he spoke with over the phone did all the work. 

Ugh, thankfully First Republic will soon have another South Bay location.







The worst bank I've dealt with in 2 decades. I spent $100K for a "premier account". My premier relationship manager doesn't pick up the phone and doesn't respond to emails. At the Palo Alto Branch you can't park because the employees park in the visitor spots. I was told to find parking on the road !!! 
They tout ease of withdrawing money around the world. What a joke. If you go to Asia they will treat you like crap unless you are fair skinned.
Their online site is a pathetic joke. I wish I had never opened this account. 

Oh and I think the positive reviews are from their own employees.







DO NOT BANK WITH HSBC!  

I had my mortgage, checking & brokerage accounts and credit card with HSBC at  one point.  They provided the WORST customer service.  The Palo Alto branch account manager never responded to my calls or emails.  The only way to talk to her was to keep calling back hoping one time she would pick up the phone.

This bank has countless, doesn't-make-sense policies.  For example,  I called to get a copy of my 1098 Form.  The rude representative said she couldn't mail one to me without my account number.  But she just looked up my account information using my SSN!  A simplest transaction must be done in writing via fax (no emails or phone).  


This bank is ridiculous!  Exercise no common sense.  Poorest customer service.  I will never give business to them again.







Let me first sum up that this is NOT your bank... "You are NOT a customer, you're an asset".

They seem nice and are very willing to help you setup an account, but that's because you've given them control of your money.  Once they have your money, they act like they are doing you a service by controlling it.

They can decide NOT to give you your money.  Yes you heard right, they refused a cash with drawl from the teller.  Not because of insufficient funds or due to not having the proper ID and account information.   They suggest that they don't always have sufficient funds to allow for cash with drawls sums that are perfectly ok at other banks (BofA for example).   If you with drawl funds regularly this is NOT the bank for you.

The place seems more like an old world investment bank.  Between the teller in the back, the sense of questioning as to why you would make a with drawl, the rude Indian manager... If you ask for your money, expect resistance and even a fight.  

With all the headache they caused, i can't say enough of how frustrating it is to work with this bank.   Yes most banks suck for one reason or another, but in the end all the other banks never refused me access to my money.







Do NOT bank here, the worst customer service I have ever experienced. The staff don't even know how their online banking works. Zero stars







